Cortical Code

Exploratory yet reproducible research

May 31, 2015

Introducing HoloViews

In this initial post, I introduce the HoloViews project by building our logo from scratch in the IPython Notebook, exploring the famous Mandelbrot set as we go along.

You may download the notebook for yourself here.

HoloViews is an open-source project that I started out of the desired to make the IPython Notebook into a productive platform for reproducible research. Although my PhD topic is in the field of computational neuroscience, I always hoped to write tools that are broadly useful to any researcher, regardless of the particular research domain.

This strategy of trying to improve scientific productivity in a general way is now paying off. After an early prototype (then called 'dataviews') a colleague of mine, Philipp Rudiger, became co-author on the project. In Feburary 2015, we were delighted to win in our category in the UK Open Source Award for our work on HoloViews.

HoloViews has matured greatly since then and we are delighted that many of our early adopters are physicists, validating the generality of our approach. In order to appeal to all researchers, we had to make sure that our examples and documentation was not domain specific and understandable by everybody. One particularly decision was coming up with a suitable logo for HoloViews.

In this first post, I'll recreate our HoloViews logo in HoloViews itself (version 1.2.0).

In [1]:
from itertools import islice
import numpy as np
import holoviews as hv

Choosing a Logo

When we started working on the HoloViews website, we knew we wanted a compelling front-page with a fun, interactive example that anybody could relate to. We needed to present some data that was simple, uncontroversial, easily recognized and aesthetically pleasing. We briefly considered displaying the famous map of the Cosmic Microwave Background before deciding that we didn't want HoloViews to come across as a physics specific library. In the end, we decided on displaying part of one of the most universally recognizable mathematical visualizations; the Mandelbrot set.

Fractals are an ideal topic to explore in order to demonstrate the capability of HoloViews due to their special properties:

  • Fractals often balance structure and randomness in an aesthetically pleasing way.
  • They can be compactly specified with very little code.
  • There are many classes of fractals and they are can be rendered in as much detailed as you desire.
  • They are familiar to different scientific researchers regardless of their particular domain.

As it turns out, there is much that can be easily explored in this area and I now have a collection of notebooks I hope to publish in the next couple of weeks, covering various topics such as the logistic map, L-systems, the chaos game and diffusion limited aggregation (among other things!)

Generating the Mandelbrot set

The HoloViews logo, is a small portion of the mandlebrot set which we will now generate using code adapted from this numpy tutorial

In [2]:
bounds = (-2,-1.4,0.8,1.4) # Area of the complex plane

def mandelbrot_generator(h,w, maxit, bounds=bounds):
    """
    Generator that yields the mandlebrot set.
    """
    (l,b,r,t) = bounds
    y,x = np.ogrid[b:t : h*1j, l:r:w*1j]
    c = x+y*1j
    z = c
    divtime = maxit + np.zeros(z.shape, dtype=int)
    for i in xrange(maxit):
        z  = z**2 + c
        diverge = z*np.conj(z) > 2**2
        div_now = diverge & (divtime==maxit)
        divtime[div_now] = i
        z[diverge] = 2
        yield divtime
        
def mandelbrot(h,w, n, maxit):
    iterable =  mandelbrot_generator(h,w, maxit)
    return next(islice(iterable, n, None))

Here, I have opted to implement a generator as it gives me the flexibility of capturing as much output from mandelbrot_generator as I choose without losing internal state. The mandelbrot function uses itertools islice to capture the nth step of generation up to maxit iterations, rendered as an array with shape \((h,w)\).

The bounds argument is the extent of the fractal in the complex plane, namely the interval from \([-2, 0.8]\) along the real axis and \([-1.4j, 1.4j]\) along the imaginary axis. The Mandelbrot Set is then the set of points in this region where the continue iteration of the following complex quadratic polynomial remains bounded:

\[z_{n+1} = z^2_n + c\]

See the wikipedia page for more information.

Visualizing the mandelbrot set

We have already imported holoviews, so let's load the ipython extension and increase the size of the HoloViews output. We will also use the 'widgets'mode for our interactive visualizations because they are more fun!

In [3]:
%load_ext holoviews.ipython
%output holomap='widgets' size=125

Let's now do a simple test:

In [4]:
arr = mandelbrot(400,400, 10, 11)
hv.Image(arr, bounds=bounds)
Out[4]:

Here we use the HoloViews Image class to visualize the generated array arr which is at iteration 10 out of a maximum of 11, with shape \((400,400)\) as expected:

In [5]:
arr.shape
Out[5]:
(400, 400)

This rendering looks a little coarse, so we may want to run a few more iterations. While the above output is not particularly impressive, with HoloViews we can launch straight into an interactive plot to explore the effect of running more iterations:

In [6]:
%%opts Image {+framewise}
hv.HoloMap({i:hv.Image(mandelbrot(400,400, i, i+1).copy(), bounds=bounds)
            for i in range(2,41)}, key_dimensions=['Iterations'])
Out[6]:

The %%opts cell magic above sets the display to be normalized framewise, so that the whole of the default 'hot' colormap is used per frame. This isn't strictly necessary but it does make the plot look prettier and more fun to play with!

Rendering at high resolution

Although iconic, we didn't want to display the whole Mandlebrot set for our homepage. Instead we wanted something recognizable as part of the Mandlebrot set with more spatial variance to look at. First, if we are going to select a small portion of the whole set, we will want to render a much larger array:

Warning: Rendering a 4000x4000 mandlebrot set will take a minute or two and requires at least 100MB of RAM!
In [7]:
render = mandelbrot(4000,4000, 50,51) # 50 iterations at 4000x4000

It is worth mentioning that implementation of mandlebrot is neither particularly fast or memory efficient! Increasing the efficiency of this code (e.g with Cython) is a project for another day...

In [8]:
render.shape
Out[8]:
(4000, 4000)

Now we now select a region of interest and use HoloViews to see exactly which bit of the fractal we have chosen to look at. To do this, we simply overlay a Bounds object on top of our Image with the * operator, then use the + operator to position the corresponding slice of the Image next to it:

In [9]:
(left, bottom, right, top) =  (-0.25, 1.12, 0.03, 0.84)
image = hv.Image(render, bounds=bounds)
roi= image[left:right, bottom:top]
image * hv.Bounds((left, bottom, right, top)) + roi
Out[9]:

That is a fairly pretty bit of the Madelbrot to select and the default 'hot' color map works well!

Adding a disk mask

Our logo consists of the selected portion of the fractal in a disk mask. This is something else we can achieve with HoloViews but first we want to be able to generate a binary array to act as our disk mask:

In [10]:
def disk(radius, resolution=512):
    lin = np.linspace(-0.25, 0.25, resolution)
    x,y = np.meshgrid(lin, lin)
    distance_from_origin = np.sqrt(x**2+y**2)
    return (distance_from_origin>=radius)

disk(0.3, resolution=7)
Out[10]:
array([[ True,  True, False, False, False,  True,  True],
       [ True, False, False, False, False, False,  True],
       [False, False, False, False, False, False, False],
       [False, False, False, False, False, False, False],
       [False, False, False, False, False, False, False],
       [ True, False, False, False, False, False,  True],
       [ True,  True, False, False, False,  True,  True]], dtype=bool)

Now we can create an Image channel corresponding to our mask, then overlay four of these images to specify the R,G,B and alpha channels in an RGB element. As we now have an image with an alpha channel, we can overaly it on top of our fractal renderings:

In [11]:
%%opts Overlay [xaxis=None yaxis=None]
mask = hv.Image(disk(0.25), value_dimensions=[hv.Dimension('Channel', range=(0,1))])
rgb_mask = hv.RGB(mask * mask * mask * mask)
hv.Image(render) * rgb_mask + hv.Image(roi.data) * rgb_mask
Out[11]:

Note that we are now work in unit-sized coordinate-system that extends 0.5 units in both the positive and negative directions along the \(x\)- and \(y\)-axes. We also declared that our image channels have unit range in value_dimensions in order for us to switch to RGBA space. Lastly we use roi.data to get access to the numpy array of our previously selected ROI.

The finishing touches

In order to demonstrate the convenient overlaying feature of HoloViews with the * operator, we wanted to annotate our logo with an additional layer of information. For this purpose, we decided to overlay a iso-contour line generated using the contours operation supplied in HoloViews.

Now we have the problem of picking a nice looking iso-level for our contour. Once again. HoloViews makes it trivial to interactively explore the effect of changing this parameter:

In [12]:
%%opts Overlay [xaxis=None yaxis=None]
data={lvl:(hv.operation.contours(hv.Image(roi.data), levels=[lvl]) * rgb_mask) for lvl in range(3,11)}
hmap = hv.HoloMap(data, key_dimensions=['Level'])
hmap
Out[12]:

Note how even our contour lines change according to a default color cycle as the level changes! An iso-contour at around 6 iterations looks good. We can now select this right out of the HoloMapdatastructure:

In [13]:
hmap[6]
Out[13]:

We can finally round off our logo with a bit of text:

In [14]:
%%opts Text (fontsize=28 family='Sans' weight='bold') Overlay [xaxis=None yaxis=None]
hmap[6] * hv.Text(0, 0.58, 'HoloViews')
Out[14]:

And that is it!

Summary

So that concludes my first notebook and post! Hopefully, I have given a nice introduction to HoloViews and demonstrated a few of the reasons why we think it is special:

  • Unlike the process of authoring a logo in a image or vector graphic editor, each step is reproducible.
  • You can present all the meaningful intermediate steps on your way towards a final result.
  • Very concise, even for generating interactive animations.

All these features use here to generate our logo should apply to the generation of any scientific figure. Together with HoloViews, the notebook format allows you to explore different ideas, keeping a record of those that work. As a result, notebooks become a great way of exploring your data, running analysis and generating figures in a reproducible way while also creating an interactive document to communicate your ideas to other people!

Additional: Relation to the Logistic map

In [15]:
%output size=250

I'll be covering the logistic map in a future notebook but I couldn't resist generating one more visualization while I had the Mandlebrot set handy. I found this beautiful illustration on Wikipedia, and I just had to see if I could quickly reproduce it with HoloViews.

It turns out that along the real axis of the Mandlebrot set, there is a nice correspondance that can be visualized between the fractal and the bifurcation diagram of the logistic map (parameterized by the growth rate \(\lambda\)) using the mapping:

\[c = \frac{\lambda}{2}\left(1 - \frac{\lambda}{2}\right)\]

In [16]:
def mapping(r):
    return (r /2.0) * ( 1 - (r/2.0))

Now we can define the logistic map (this code will be discussed in a future notebook):

In [17]:
def logistic_map(gens=20, init=0.5, growth=0.5):
    population = [init]
    for gen in range(gens-1):
        current = population[gen]
        population.append(current * growth * (1 - current))
    return population

Now we get the the positions of the bifurcation points (some of which are missing from that page and that I estimated instead):

In [18]:
bifurcations = [1, 3, 3.4494, 3.5440, 3.5644, 3.7381, 3.7510, 3.8284, 3.8481]

And plot them on our bifurcation diagram after transforming the \(x\)-axis with the mapping function:

In [19]:
growth_rates = np.linspace(0.9, 4, 1000)
bifurcation_diagram = hv.Points([(mapping(rate), pop) for rate in growth_rates for 
             (gen, pop) in enumerate(logistic_map(gens=200, growth=rate))
             if gen>=100])  # Discard the first 100 generations to view attractors more easily
In [20]:
%%opts Image (cmap='Reds') Points (s=1 color='g') Curve (color='teal' linewidth=1) HLine (color='k' linestyle='--')
vlines = hv.Overlay([hv.Curve([(mapping(pos),0), ((mapping(pos),1.4))]) for pos in bifurcations])
hv.Image(mandelbrot(800,800, 45, 46).copy(), bounds=(-2, -1.4, 0.8, 1.4)) * bifurcation_diagram * hv.HLine(0) * vlines
Out[20]:

Beautiful!

What's more, this leads up nicely to my upcoming notebook on the Logistic Map.
